+    \subsection{Orthodox ropelength and thickness convention}
+        \label{subsec:orthodox_ropelength_thickness_convention}
+
+        \textbf{[ORTHODOX / CANON CONVENTION].}
+        For any tame closed centerline representative $\gamma_K$ of a swirl-string
+        topology class $K$, the radius-convention thickness is the reach of the
+        embedded curve,
+        \begin{align}
+            \operatorname{Thi}_{\rm rad}(\gamma_K)
+            =
+            \operatorname{reach}(\gamma_K)
+            =
+            \operatorname{NIR}(\gamma_K),
+            \label{eq:canon_thickness_reach}
+        \end{align}
+        where $\operatorname{NIR}$ denotes the normal injectivity radius.  The
+        radius-convention ropelength is
+        \begin{align}
+            \operatorname{Rop}_{\rm rad}(\gamma_K)
+            =
+            \frac{\operatorname{Len}(\gamma_K)}
+                 {\operatorname{Thi}_{\rm rad}(\gamma_K)}.
+            \label{eq:canon_ropelength_rad}
+        \end{align}
+        Some knot-theory literature uses a diameter convention.  SST fixes the
+        radius convention in Eq.~\eqref{eq:canon_ropelength_rad}; if a diameter
+        convention is imported, it must be converted by
+        \begin{align}
+            \operatorname{Rop}_{\rm diam}
+            =
+            \frac12\,\operatorname{Rop}_{\rm rad}.
+            \label{eq:ropelength_diameter_conversion}
+        \end{align}
+
+        \textbf{[ORTHODOX].}
+        Ropelength minimizers exist for tame knot and link types.  Such tight
+        representatives are $C^{1,1}$ and have bounded curvature, but they need
+        not be globally $C^2$ and need not be unique
+        \cite{CantarellaKusnerSullivan2002Ropelength}.  Polygonal constrained
+        tightening represents the same finite-thickness problem by active
+        struts, kinks, and a projected constrained gradient
+        \cite{AshtonCantarellaPiatekRawdon2010Ridgerunner}.
+
+        \textbf{[CANON RULE].}
+        The bare topological class $K$ does not by itself determine a unique
+        physical particle representative.  Any mass, screening, or stability
+        calculation that uses ropelength must state which representative
+        $\gamma_K$, which radius convention, and which relaxation protocol are
+        being used.  The physical centerline length is written
+        \begin{align}
+            L_{\rm phys}(K)
+            =
+            a_{\rm core}(K)\,\operatorname{Rop}_{\rm rad}(\gamma_K),
+            \label{eq:lphys_from_ropelength}
+        \end{align}
+        with $a_{\rm core}(K)=\operatorname{Thi}_{\rm rad}(\gamma_K)$ unless a
+        separately derived resolved-tube radius is specified.
+
